Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a medium #saucepan{} with a tight-fitting
#lid{}. Stir in the @Basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the
boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still
covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve
(the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim the @Courgette{1}, then quarter lengthways. Chop into 2cm chunks.

Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain the @King Prawns{300%g}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. When hot, add the
courgette and cook until charred, ~{6-8%minutes} total. Turn only every couple of
mins. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Once charred, lower the heat to medium and stir in the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g}
and @Pasanda style seasoning{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder).
Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @Creme Fraiche{75%g}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @sugar{1%tsp} and
@water for the sauce{100%ml} to the courgette pan. Stir to combine and bring to
the boil.

Stir in the prawns and simmer until cooked through, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the prawns are cooked, stir through the @Butter{20%g} until melted, then
remove from the heat.

Taste the curry and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of
water if it's a little too thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then share between your #bowls{}.

Top with the prawn curry. Sprinkle over the @toasted flaked almonds{15%g} to
finish. Enjoy!